            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                New York&#44; June 13<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#34;87<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and Dear Sir&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I take pleasure in<lb/> informing you that since the 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> inst. I<lb/> am engaged to be married to Miss<lb/> Sarah Weil daughter of Jonas Weil Esq<lb/> one of the friends and supporters of our<lb/> institution.  I also take pleasure in<lb/> congratulating you upon the degree of<lb/> L.L.D. which&#44; <del>has I</del> as I hear&#44; has just<lb/> been conferred upon you&#44; may you bear<lb/> your new dignity for many years in health<lb/> and strength and be enabled through<lb/> it to prosecute even more successfully<lb/> and powerfully the noble objects and<lb/> sublime ideals for which you have hither<lb/> to labored so constantly and unswervingly.<lb/>  I suppose you have been already informed<lb/> that the Advisory Board&#44; at their last<lb/> meeting&#44; decided to recommend that<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>a private examination by ministers be<lb/> held on the 28<hi rend="sup">th</hi> inst&#44; leaving a public ex&#45;<lb/>hibition for the fall and that a higher<lb/> department be called into existence for<lb/> the next term.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping to see you soon in New York&#44; I<lb/> remain<lb/></p>
            <p>very respectfully yours<lb/>
                Bernard Drachman<lb/>
                439 E. 56<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
